Abaycosa nanica

resembles 

Abaycosa paraguensis

in the coloration 
Spination pattern
and the presence of only one distal macrosetae on the tip of the male cymbium. Males can be recognized by the basal branch of the median apophysis curved apically (Figs 
3E, F
; 
6B
) and females by the separated copulatory openings (Figs 
3C
; 
8B
), that are almost touching on the middle in 

A. paraguensis

(Figs 
3D
; 
9B
).

Known from north Paraguay, south of Bolivia and Brazil, north Argentina and Uruguay (Fig. 
10A
).
